"1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1672":"1672","21 May 1609":"21 May 1609","1709":"1709","1615":"1615","1658":"1658","Windsberg, Pirmasens, Rheinland-Pfalz, Deutschland":"Windsberg, Pirmasens, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Zug, Szwajcaria":"Zug, Switzerland","Zweibrücken, Bayern, Germany":"Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Speck","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from Middle High German <i>spec</i> ‘bacon’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a seller of bacon or a pork butcher, or a nickname for a fat person.","German: topographic name from Middle High German <i>speck(e)</i> ‘log bridge or road’.","German: habitational name from any of the places called Speck, Specke, or Specken."],"variants":[{"name":"Speake","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Speke in Lancashire, named in Old English with <i>spēc</i> ‘small branch, twig’.","nickname from Middle English <i>spek(e)</i>, <i>spec</i> (Old French <i>espech(e)</i>, <i>espek</i>). The name was interchangeable with the synonymous name   Speight  . <i>Espec</i> or <i>Espek</i> is recorded as a nickname in Normandy from 1036."]},{"name":"Speckmann","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a path through a swampy area, Middle Low German <i>specke</i>. In some cases it may have been a metonymic occupational name for someone who constructed such paths, usually from brush, soil, or the like.","North German: habitational name for someone from any of the places called Specke or Specken in northern Germany and Holland.","German: variant of   Speck   1, with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]}]},{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]},{"name":"Katharina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Katherine</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anna Katharina Speck was born in 1585, in Zug, Switzerland, her father, Jacob Speck, was 25 and her mother, Eva Knoepflin, was 28. She married Nicolaus Hanss on 21 May 1609, in Bavaria, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1645, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1585–1645":"1585–1645","1577–Male":"1577–Surnud","1585–Female":"1585–Surnud","1588–1658":"1588–1658","1593–1634":"1593–1634","1594–1664":"1594–1664","1596–Female":"1596–Surnud","1585–1672":"1585–1672","–Male":"Surnud","1615–1709":"1615–1709","1560–Male":"1560–Surnud","1558–Female":"1558–Surnud","1594":"1594","1560":"1560","1593":"1593","1558":"1558","1645":"1645","1634":"1634","1588":"1588","1577":"1577","1664":"1664","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1672":"1672","21 May 1609":"21. mai 1609","1709":"1709","1615":"1615","1658":"1658","Windsberg, Pirmasens, Rheinland-Pfalz, Deutschland":"Windsberg, Pirmasens, Rheinland-Pfalz, Saksamaa","Zug, Szwajcaria":"Zug, Šveits","Zweibrücken, Bayern, Germany":"Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1585–1645":"1585–1645","1577–Male":"1577–Kuollut","1585–Female":"1585–Kuollut","1588–1658":"1588–1658","1593–1634":"1593–1634","1594–1664":"1594–1664","1596–Female":"1596–Kuollut","1585–1672":"1585–1672","–Male":"Kuollut","1615–1709":"1615–1709","1560–Male":"1560–Kuollut","1558–Female":"1558–Kuollut","1594":"1594","1560":"1560","1593":"1593","1558":"1558","1645":"1645","1634":"1634","1588":"1588","1577"